  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Here's an overview of the legislative evolution to combat money laundering:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- 1970 Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) in US\n- Initial focus on reporting large cash transactions\n- Limited international cooperation\n\n2. 1980s Developments\n- Growing recognition of money laundering as global issue\n- First international anti-money laundering (AML) guidelines\n- Increased financial reporting requirements\n\n3. 1990s Milestones\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- Enhanced international collaboration\n- More comprehensive compliance regulations\n\n4. Post-9/11 Legislation\n- USA PATRIOT Act expanded AML provisions\n- Increased focus on terrorism financing\n- Stricter Know Your Customer (KYC) requirements\n- Enhanced customer due diligence\n\n5. Recent Trends\n- Digital currency regulations\n- Cryptocurrency tracking\n- Beneficial ownership transparency\n- Enhanced cross-border information sharing\n- Artificial intelligence and machine learning in detection\n\n6. Global Regulatory Framework\n- More standardized international guidelines\n- Increased penalties for non-compliance\n- Expanded scope of regulated financial institutions\n\nThe legislative approach has progressively become more comprehensive and technologically sophisticated.",
